WinMX (also known as WinMX Media Exchange) is a peer-to-peer file sharing program designed for the Microsoft Windows operating system. It was developed by Sharman Networks and released in 1997.

In the early days of the program, it was commonly referred to as McMA (McAfee's Media Agent), but the name WinMX was officially adopted in 2000.

The original WinMX software was designed to be a fork of the Gnutella network, which was an open source peer-to-peer network that allowed users to share files without a central server. As a result, the WinMX software allowed users to search for and download files from other users on the network, without having to rely on a central server.

While WinMX is no longer available for download, many of its features can be found in modern file sharing programs such as FrostWire, BitTorrent, and Vuze.
